[4] Virginia: horse
Date: Mon 17 Aug 2020 4:01 PM EDT
Source: Augusta Free Press (AFP) [edited]
https://augustafreepress.com/chesapeake-horse-tests-positive-for-eastern-equine-encephalitis-west-nile-virus/


The Virginia Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services [VDACS] confirms a horse stabled in Chesapeake tested positive for eastern equine encephalitis and West Nile virus.

The female quarter horse was euthanized on [7 Aug 2020] after showing severe neurological signs.

No other horses on the farm are showing signs of EEE or WNV.

VDACS encourages horse owners to speak with their veterinarians about vaccinating their horses for EEE and WNV. The mortality rate for WNV is 30 percent and up to 90 percent for EEE.

Vaccinations are effective for 6 to 12 months.

Both EEE and WNV are mosquito-borne illnesses. Typical signs include staggering, circling, depression, loss of appetite, and sometimes fever and blindness. There is no cure for the disease, but it can be prevented through vaccination. Other prevention methods include destroying standing water breeding sites for mosquitoes, use of insect repellents, and removing animals from mosquito-infested areas during peak biting times, usually dusk to dawn. Once a horse has been bitten by an infected mosquito, it may take three to ten days for signs of the disease to appear.

For more information on how to control mosquitoes around horses, visit http://vdacs.virginia.gov/animals-eastern-equine-encephalitis.shtml.

Horse owners may also contact VDACS' Office of Veterinary Services or consult their local veterinarian.

