[HealthMap/ProMED map of South Carolina, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7689139,22603
South Carolina County map: https://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/states/south-carolina/south-carolina-county-map.html

This is a very busy mosquito season. The article on mosquito trapping (see [2] above] is very important. When counties/states are testing mosquitos, they are looking for what kind of disease season it is likely to be. Horse owners: heed the warning. This is a very busy mosquito season and consequently we see a lot of mosquito borne disease in our horses.

Eastern equine encephalitis is preventable. The vaccine for EEE is usually combined with some other mosquito borne diseases such as West Nile virus (WNV) (mentioned in this update), and western equine encephalitis (WEE). Additionally, these usually have tetanus included. Hence, a lot of protection for the dollars. The vaccine is a series of 2-3 vaccines given 3-4 weeks apart.

EEE wanes the fastest and in areas where the prevalence of the disease is high, horse owners are encouraged to revaccinate approximately every 3-4 months for best protection. - Mod.TG]
